Hey, author of Dragons next door. It's a bit late reply from me, so I hope you're still here.

I like the first person, non-greentext format. I would argue, that shorter paragraphs are needed in the parts where there isn't dialogue. For example, the lines 1 and 3, they're just walls of text, kinda hard to read. Just put some breaks in there where they fit, and it should be fine.

The punctuation is a bit questionable. For example, Line 67, 'Is that a normal thing or,?'. Inconsistent usage of commas and periods at some parts. Also, like six usages of ' !, ' which I'm pretty sure isn't a good thing.

There are some words missing every now and then.

Usage of parentheses is a bit odd, especially with the kind of 'train of thought' -style of the prose. I feel like those things should either be included normally, or simply left out.

The dialogue is pretty great. It feels natural in most places. Some parts are a bit eh, for example the part with Tarran/Tarren. The argument betwen Gwen and him felt kind of forced in.

I feel like there are some inconsistencies, but it could also be just me missing something.
For example;
The lines 202-204
Granddad gives Gwen a plushie "a few days after hatching", and she mentions that it was "one of the last thing he gave me before he passed away"
Feels a bit weird. 'one of the last things' kinda assumes that he gave her gifts before that, too. But that was only a few days after hatching?

Also, Tarren or Tarran are both used. That's probably a mistake.

Still, I'm looking forward to seeing more. Love me some casually nude dragons.

I'm certain everyone here knows how a baby grows up (at least somewhat), and how vulnerable they are for so long. Now I have no fucking idea where this thought originally came from, but wouldn't anthro kids be more like animals? I mean, I assume that they'de probably look a good deal less like the fat little things humans give birth to, but that's not what I mean. Does anyone else here think that young anthros would grow different when they're babies? Young animals grow pretty quickly even if they stay with their mother for a while. For some reason my brain tells me that anthro toddlers would grow a good deal faster than human ones would. They'de be more mobile, and a lot more trouble as they grow up in the early stages before slowing back down as they become kids. They'de look a lot more like tiny weirdly shaped animals than they would a "baby" at a certain point. But I also realize putting something like that in a story which could be somewhat odd or offputting needs a vote, or at least feedback. So I'm going to post a poll, look at responses if any pop up, and look at the poll results later just to get a feel of how people feel about young anthros growing faster and all that.
